BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/Untitled-design-9.jpg
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260716T054010Z
DESCRIPTION:Trees are more than sources of shade\, beauty and sustenance—they are living indicators of environmental change. Join us for an engaging workshop with SeasonWatch\, a pan-India citizen science initiative that studies the seasonal cycles of trees to better understand the impacts of climate change. Through observing the leaves\, flowers and fruits of common trees\, participants will discover how seasonal changes reveal shifts in our environment and why long-term monitoring is vital for climate research.\n\nThe workshop with Sayee Girdhari combines both indoor and outdoor learning\, offering insight into how everyday observations can contribute to scientific research.\n\n\n\nThis event is in conjunction with our ongoing permanent exhibition Beneath the Turning Sky. \n\n\n\n
DTEND:20260719T073000Z
DTSTART:20260719T043000Z
SUMMARY:Trees as Climate Witness
UID:1331@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/trees-as-climate-witness/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/Screenshot-2026-07-15-200131.png
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260716T130256Z
DESCRIPTION:A Moving Line gathers more than 250 works to trace how India has told stories in sequence across fifteen hundred years. Come\, witness both the creation of new visual identities and the evolution of a nation through a vast body of works across time and space as Khushi Bansal from the MAP team guides you through it. Follow a single line from a temple wall in Bengaluru to the touchscreen\, and watch a country tell its stories.\n\nThis programme is part of the celebration of the opening of A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling. 
DTEND:20260726T083000Z
DTSTART:20260726T073000Z
SUMMARY:Panels\, Pages and Presentations
UID:1343@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/panels-pages-and-presentations/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/Website-cover-images-new-2025-05-02T115226.170.png
CATEGORIES:Film Screenings,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260714T070149Z
DESCRIPTION:Join us for an evening of short film screenings\, curated by Deepthi\, that bring into focus stories of neurodivergent identity\, resilience\, and authentic connection. Through intimate and thought-provoking narratives\, these films explore the realities of neurodivergent lives and the parents of neurodivergent children.\n\nSpanning diverse parental experiences\, the screenings invite audiences to engage with stories that challenge stigma through the power of storytelling. These films offer a window into the complex inner worlds that exist beyond labels\, celebrating the creativity and unique perspectives that come with thinking differently and embracing acceptance.\n\nThe programme aims to create space for dialogue grounded in understanding\, mutual support\, and the quiet power of shared experience. Whether you are neurodivergent yourself or seeking to understand better\, this evening is a celebration of the struggle\, acceptance\, and brilliance of neurodivergent individuals and their caregivers/parents.
DTEND:20260719T113000Z
DTSTART:20260719T093000Z
SUMMARY:Stories of Neurodivergence: A Short Film Screenings
UID:1339@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/stories-of-neurodivergence-a-short-film-screenings/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/Screenshot-2026-07-15-192302.png
CATEGORIES:Panel Discussion,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260716T130326Z
DESCRIPTION:Image Credits: Panels from Will to Live by Mia Jose\nComic artist Mia Jose and graphic novelist Simon Lamouret will converse about their experiences and the inspirations that led them to create their works. This session focuses on identity\, culture and the city\, drawing on their individual practices and the spaces their works are rooted in. The notion of city is rooted in some of their works\, which helps us see a space as one’s company\, a space of constant changes and as identity. Get to know about their thought processes\, artistic inspirations and how the country they grew up in influenced their works. \n\nThis programme is part of the celebration of the opening of A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling.
DTEND:20260725T123000Z
DTSTART:20260725T113000Z
SUMMARY:Artist-in-Dialogue
UID:1340@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/artist-in-dialogue/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/6761a8d5-7abc-4ece-9177-6c5d56422bd4-e1784286828237.jpg
CATEGORIES:Performances,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260717T115359Z
DESCRIPTION:Image credit: Sonia Dechamps\nJoin graphic novelist David Prudhomme for a live drawing performance accompanied by a selection of music chosen by the artist. As images unfold in real time\, Prudhomme invites audiences into the intimate relationship between sound\, memory\, and visual storytelling.\n\nThe performance will be followed by a talk on his work\, with a focus on the role of music in his graphic novels. Music is central to Rébétiko and Rébétissa (Futuropolis)\, his two-part exploration of the outlawed Greek musical tradition of the 1930s and the histories\, communities\, and cultural landscapes it emerged from.\n\nThis programme is part of the celebration of the opening of A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling. 
DTEND:20260726T103000Z
DTSTART:20260726T093000Z
SUMMARY:Live Drawing
UID:1352@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/live-drawing/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/430-x-400-px-Widget-1.jpg
CATEGORIES:Book Launch,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260718T130436Z
DESCRIPTION:Join us for the launch of MAP’s latest publication\, A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling\, is a first of its kind anthology tracing India’s long and rich history of visual storytelling\, from temple walls and painted scrolls to comics\, graphic novels\, and webcomics.\n\nThe book launch is followed by a panel discussion with graphic artist and researcher Sarita Sundar\, comics archivist\, researcher Arun Prasad\, publication designer Mira Malhotra and artist Partha Banik\, moderated by Saba Nehal from the MAP team.\n\nThis programme is part of the celebration of the opening of A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling.
DTEND:20260725T103000Z
DTSTART:20260725T103000Z
SUMMARY:A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling
UID:1348@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/a-moving-line-1500-years-of-indian-visual-storytelling/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/Screenshot-2026-07-15-202955.png
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260717T073554Z
DESCRIPTION:Do you remember Shikari Shambu? What about Suppandi? We’ve all read stories of these beloved comic characters but do you wonder how they were created? Who drew them\; what stories that came before inspired their creators\; Did their designs change? Join us for a guided walk in Kannada led by Niharika Shenoy from the MAP team to wonder about these and more questions. Get a sneak peek into the curatorial perspective and the history of Indian visual storytelling.\n\nThis programme is part of the celebration of the opening of A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling. 
DTEND:20260725T113000Z
DTSTART:20260725T103000Z
SUMMARY:Ink mattu kathe - A Kannada Guided Walk
UID:1345@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/ink-mattu-kathe-a-kannada-guided-walk/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/Screenshot-2026-07-13-184758.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260715T054234Z
DESCRIPTION:Facilitated by The Open Studio Project\, a collaborative practice by artists and art psychotherapists Devika Sundar and Roshni Bhatia\, this workshop invites participants into an exploration of memory\, myth\, and imagination through creative practice.\n\nBeginning with a shared exploration of the exhibition Beneath the Turning Sky\, participants will draw from their own lived experiences\, memories\, and imagination to create visual narratives that weave together inner and outer worlds and landscapes. Through image-making\, they are invited to explore the meeting points between memory\, myth\, place\, and the natural world\, considering how stories—both inherited and imagined—shape the ways we understand ourselves and the environments we inhabit. Rather than focusing on artistic skill or finished artworks\, the workshop emphasizes the creative process as a space for curiosity\, reflection\, dialogue and meaning-making.\n\nTaking place as part of Disability Pride Month\, the workshop is grounded in the values of accessibility\, inclusivity\, and care. Designed as a welcoming space for creativity and conversation\, it embraces diverse ways of learning\, making\, and participating\, inviting everyone to engage at their own pace and in ways that feel meaningful to them.\n\nNo prior artistic experience is required\, and all materials will be provided.
DTEND:20260719T073000Z
DTSTART:20260719T053000Z
SUMMARY:Memory\, Myth & Making
UID:1338@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/memory-myth-making/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/TC.2026.107-1.jpg
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260716T130310Z
DESCRIPTION:Image Credit: Panel from Vyasa: The Beginning by Sankha Banerjee\nJoin us for a guided walkthrough of the A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling as its curator Amruta Patil narrates the stories this country tells through lines. In this exhibition\, one can witness both the creation of new visual identities and the evolution of a nation through a vast body of works across time and space. Here\, kaavad and pattachitra scroll sitting alongside Amar Chitra Katha and Tinkle. Chacha Chaudhary next to the Phantom\, while contemporary graphic novels and web comics continue conversations that began centuries ago. \n\nThis programme is part of the celebration of the opening of A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling. 
DTEND:20260725T063000Z
DTSTART:20260725T053000Z
SUMMARY:Reading Between the Panels: A Curator’s Walkthrough
UID:1342@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/reading-between-the-panels-a-curators-walkthrough/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/Untitled-design-10.jpg
CATEGORIES:Talks,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260714T095452Z
DESCRIPTION:What does it mean to belong? Who is responsible for creating the conditions in which every person can participate and feel valued?\n\nFor many autistic individuals and their families\, everyday life means navigating systems\, spaces and expectations that were not designed with them in mind\; leaving the work of adapting\, advocating and finding support to fall on families themselves.\n\nPresented as part of MAP’s Disability Pride Month 2026 programming\, this conversation brings together Bela Joshi and Sneha Joshi\, mother and daughter\, and mother and sister of an autistic family member\, in a dialogue shaped by lived experience and over a decade of work at Colours Centre for Learning. Across two generations\, they trace how the questions families ask\, and the support they seek change over time.\n\nAs a young mother raising an autistic son when awareness and services were scarce\, Bela found little institutional support\, and built her own community instead. Years later\, Sneha's questions as a sibling were different: about identity\, belonging and what it means to grow up alongside disability\, with even less language available for them. That process of finding\, and often having to build support shaped their understanding of interdependence: the idea that none of us moves through the world unsupported\, and that belonging is built by communities learning to rely on one another\, not by individuals becoming self-sufficient. It is also what grew into Colours Centre for Learning.\n\nTogether\, they bring a rare combination to this conversation: two generations\, two vantage points inside the same family\, and over a decade of shared commitment. Bela and Sneha ask what meaningful support can look like today for autistic individuals and for the families around them. Rather than framing inclusion as something families must continually strive for alone\, they invite us to imagine belonging as interdependence in practice: a responsibility shared across communities\, institutions and generations.\n\nThis programme is presented as part of MAP's Disability Pride Month 2026 programming.
DTEND:20260719T130000Z
DTSTART:20260719T120000Z
SUMMARY:Who Is Responsible for Belonging?
UID:1335@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/who-is-responsible-for-belonging/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/Untitled-design-11.jpg
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260716T090838Z
DESCRIPTION:How do the materials we work with shape the stories we tell about ourselves?\n\nIn this workshop\, artist Riya introduces participants to 'Botanical Beings'\, beginning with a conversation around her practice\, participants will look closely at her work before creating their own works using preserved flowers. Working slowly and intuitively\, the session invites participants to engage with the materials through observation\, reflection\, and play\, while exploring making as a practice of presence and care.\n\nTogether\, participants will consider how the ways we engage with the world can shape what we create\, and how the works we make can become reflections of our own ways of seeing and being.\n\nThis programme is exclusively for 18–25 year olds.\n\nThis session is conducted as part of our engagements for the MAP Youth Collective. The MAP Youth Collective is a community for young people (18-25 year olds) to engage with the arts and culture sector. The collective is for\, of and by young people — to explore our shared identities and interests through art.
DTEND:20260719T120000Z
DTSTART:20260719T090000Z
SUMMARY:Botanical Beings
UID:1347@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/botanical-beings/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/TC.2026.077.jpg
CATEGORIES:Listening Session,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260717T103914Z
DESCRIPTION:Image credit: Arun Prasad's Comic Archive\nYou’ve probably seen your favorite comic character on the big screens. For the longest time\, comic books have been adapted into movies\, television shows or animated series to bring them to life\, but have you ever heard your comics?\n\nJoin us for a live listening session where comic books come alive through vinyl records from Arun Prasad's Comic Archive. Experience your favorite stories in a whole new way of enjoying comics\, as you hear from Arun Prasad about his journey of collecting comics. \n\nThis programme is part of the celebration of the opening of A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling.
DTEND:20260725T073000Z
DTSTART:20260725T063000Z
SUMMARY:Listening to Comics
UID:1351@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/listening-to-comics/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/BTS-InstallViews-web-5.jpg
CATEGORIES:Drop-in Sessions,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260715T154220Z
DESCRIPTION:Ever wondered why most museums have Nataraja or Dancing Shiva in their collections? It is a result of multiple phenomena that happened during the 18th century. Art history\, modern dance\, physics\, West’s fascination for Eastern culture and more\, parallely played a part.\n\nThis month’s edition of Up\, Close and Centre will feature Abiraami from the MAP team. She looks at Nataraja from our second permanent exhibition Beneath the Turning Sky\, through the MAP Collection.\n\nUp\, Close &amp\; Centre is a series that allows audiences to engage with art in deeper and more meaningful ways by delving into the context\, narratives and makings of one artwork from our collection\, chosen by our team members.
DTEND:20260721T120000Z
DTSTART:20260721T113000Z
SUMMARY:Up\, Close and Centre: Nataraja
UID:1332@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/up-close-and-centre-nataraja/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/Screenshot-2026-07-15-202407.png
CATEGORIES:Drop-in Sessions,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260716T125505Z
DESCRIPTION:Image Credits: Archives of Comics Culture Collective\nMeet &amp\; Greet the artists whose work is on the walls of the galleries you will scroll through. A good chance to interact with them to understand their journey as an illustrator/writer\, ask questions or get an autograph!\n\nThis programme is part of the celebration of the opening of A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling. 
DTEND:20260726T070000Z
